
Title: Conformal Causal-Physics Models: Unifying Causal Discovery, Differentiable Contact, and Finite-Sample Safety for Zero-Shot Sim-to-Real Transfer  

Author: Ouadi Maakoul  

Working Code: SIM-ROBOT-2026-003

---

Abstract

Sim-to-real transfer remains the primary bottleneck to scalable embodied AI. Policies trained in simulation exhibit catastrophic failure when deployed on physical hardware due to structural mismatches in contact dynamics, material properties, and sensor behavior that cannot be captured by parametric domain randomization. This dissertation reframes the sim-to-real gap as a partially identifiable structural causal model (SCM) over physical discrepancy variables, rather than unstructured noise.

We introduce CausalSim++, a unified framework that combines three components: 1) Bayesian causal discovery of the sim-to-real gap with sample-complexity bounds for Markov equivalence class recovery, 2) differentiable neuro-analytic contact dynamics whose neural residuals are structurally constrained by the discovered SCM, and 3) conformal causal safety filtering that provides finite-sample, distribution-free coverage guarantees even under imperfect causal identification. 

Our key theoretical result shows that causal conditioning reduces the volume of conformal prediction sets compared to black-box approaches, yielding tighter safety bounds and fewer unnecessary interventions. Unlike foundation world models that provide temporal consistency but lack mechanistic guarantees, or residual dynamics methods that learn black-box corrections, CausalSim++ offers simultaneous causal interpretability, formal stability for contact-rich systems, and certified safety from ≤15 real-world calibration rollouts.

We validate the framework on REALM-Causal, an extension of the REALM benchmark with ground-truth SCM annotations and contact-rich tasks. CausalSim++ achieves Sim2Real Transfer Ratio ≥0.85 on deformable manipulation and connector insertion while maintaining 5ms end-to-end latency on Jetson Orin, outperforming Cosmos Policy, LingBot-VA, and Sym2Real baselines on tasks requiring precise contact reasoning. The work establishes that causal structure is the missing inductive bias for certifiable sim-to-real transfer.

Keywords: sim-to-real transfer, causal discovery, differentiable simulation, conformal prediction, safety-critical robotics, contact dynamics

