Introduction

The promise of simulation-trained embodied AI is offset by a harsh reality: policies achieving 99% success in simulation routinely collapse to <20% on physical hardware. The cause is not insufficient data or poor optimization. It is a structural mismatch between idealized physics engines and the unmodeled, causal mechanisms governing real-world contact, deformation, and sensing.

The Limitation of Parametric Approaches
For a decade, domain randomization (DR) has been the de facto solution: randomize simulator parameters \theta \sim p(\theta) and train policies robust to the induced variation. DR implicitly assumes \mathcal{P}_{\text{real}} \in \{\mathcal{P}_\theta : \theta \in \Theta\}. This fails when reality contains dynamics outside the simulator’s parametric family: contact hysteresis, material fatigue, joint compliance, and thermal drift. These are not noise. They are mechanisms with causal structure that DR cannot randomize because the simulator lacks knobs to express them.

A Note on Terminology: Two Meanings of ‘Causal’
Contemporary literature uses “causal” in two distinct senses that must be disambiguated:  
Temporal causal attention (Astra 2026, diffusion video models): Autoregressive masking of future tokens to enforce p(x_t|x_{<t}). Guarantees temporal consistency in video prediction but provides no mechanistic understanding.  
Structural causal models (this thesis): Explicit directed acyclic graphs over physical variables with $do$-calculus semantics. Supports interventional reasoning, identifiability analysis, and gap attribution.  

This thesis goes beyond temporal masking to structural discovery. We use the SCM to correct dynamics and certify safety; we do not merely predict pixels.

Thesis Statement
The sim-to-real gap is fundamentally a structural mismatch problem, not merely parametric noise. By unifying 1) partially identifiable causal SCMs for gap discovery, 2) differentiable hybrid contact dynamics constrained by causal structure, and 3) conformal prediction for finite-sample safety certification, we enable policies trained purely in simulation to deploy zero-shot in the real world with bounded performance degradation, interpretable failure modes, and distribution-free safety guarantees. This framework does not replace foundation world models; it provides the formal physical consistency, causal interpretability, and deployment certificates that vision-centric predictors currently lack, at the cost of requiring a differentiable simulator and a small real-world calibration set.

Core Contributions
Causal SCM Formulation: We formalize the reality gap as a partially identifiable SCM over physical discrepancy nodes with sample-complexity bounds \tilde{O}(|\delta|\log|\delta|/\epsilon^2) for Markov equivalence class recovery. Bayesian model averaging provides robustness when perfect identifiability fails.
Causal-Structured Hybrid Dynamics: Differentiable rigid-body simulation augmented with neural residuals whose connectivity is masked by the discovered causal graph. We prove exponential ISS stability under PD control when residuals are Lipschitz-bounded.
Conformal Causal Safety Filtering: Conformal prediction on causally corrected residuals yields finite-sample coverage guarantees. Corollary 3.1: Causal conditioning reduces prediction set volume versus black-box conformal methods, giving tighter safety bounds.
Intervention-Supervised Causal Encoder: Maps observations to disentangled causal states using sim pretraining + minimal real finetuning, enabling deployment without ground-truth state.

