1.1.2 The Inadequacy of Domain Randomization

Domain Randomization (DR) assumes \mathcal{P}_{\text{real}} \in \left\{ \mathcal{P}_\theta : \theta \in \Theta \right\} for simulator parameters \theta \sim p(\theta). Training a policy robust to p(\theta) ensures deployment lies within the training distribution. DR succeeds when mismatch is parametric.

DR fails catastrophically when reality contains structural mismatches: dynamics outside the simulator’s parametric family. Examples include:

Contact hysteresis: Force-displacement relationships during loading/unloading differ in ways not captured by Coulomb friction coefficients
Material fatigue: Physical properties change over repeated interaction; rigid-body simulators assume stationarity  
Unmodeled compliance: Joint flexibility, actuator backlash, and transmission elasticity are simplified or omitted
Exogenous drift: Thermal expansion, battery sag, lubricant viscosity introduce time-varying dynamics with no parametric representation

