1.2.2 Interventions and Causal Discovery

Actions a_t serve as perfect interventions on the action node: we set a_t independently of other variables. Controlled experiments (adding payloads, changing surfaces) probe causal relationships.

Definition 1.2 (Intervention). An intervention \text{do}(\mathbf{X} = \mathbf{x}) replaces structural equations for \mathbf{X} \subseteq \mathbf{V} with $X := x$. The distribution is P(\mathbf{V} \mid \text{do}(\mathbf{X} = \mathbf{x})).

Interventional data is critical for identifiability. Let \mathcal{D}_{\text{obs}} be observational data under fixed policy and \mathcal{D}_{\text{int}} be interventional data with varied actions. Their combination enables discovery of causal structure unidentifiable from \mathcal{D}_{\text{obs}} alone.

