Chapter 2: Causal SCM Formulation and Partial Identifiability

The fundamental premise of this dissertation is that the sim-to-real gap is not merely parametric noise but arises from structural mismatches—unmodeled physical mechanisms that lie outside the simulator's parametric family. This chapter develops the theoretical framework for discovering, representing, and reasoning about these structural mismatches through the lens of Structural Causal Models (SCMs). We formalize the sim-to-real gap as a partially identifiable SCM over discrepancy nodes, derive sample-complexity bounds for recovery under intervention, and establish performance guarantees when only Markov equivalence classes can be identified. The framework is grounded in recent advances in causal discovery for robotics, validated against the CausalDynamics benchmark, and positioned relative to concurrent causal world models.

---

2.1 Structural Causal Models for Robotic Dynamics

2.1.1 Formal Definition

A Structural Causal Model provides a formal language for describing the mechanistic relationships among variables in a system. Unlike purely statistical models that capture only correlations, SCMs encode how variables influence one another and support reasoning about interventions and counterfactuals.

Definition 2.1 (Structural Causal Model for Sim-to-Real Dynamics). An SCM \mathcal{C} for robotic dynamics is a tuple \mathcal{C} = \langle \mathbf{V}, \mathbf{E}, \mathbf{F}, P(\mathbf{U}) \rangle where:

1. \mathbf{V} = \mathbf{S} \cup \mathbf{A} \cup \Delta is the set of endogenous nodes, partitioned into:
   · \mathbf{S} = \{s_t, s_{t+1}, \dot{s}_t, \dot{s}_{t+1}, \dots\}: observable state variables (positions, velocities, joint torques)
   · \mathbf{A} = \{a_t, a_{t+1}, \dots\}: action variables (commanded torques, joint targets)
   · \Delta = \{\delta_1, \delta_2, \dots, \delta_k\}: discrepancy nodes representing unmodeled physical mechanisms
2. \mathbf{E} \subseteq \mathbf{V} \times \mathbf{V} is a set of directed edges encoding direct causal dependencies. The graph \mathcal{G} = (\mathbf{V}, \mathbf{E}) is assumed to be acyclic (DAG).
3. \mathbf{F} = \{f_v\}_{v \in \mathbf{V}} is a collection of structural equations such that for each v \in \mathbf{V}:
   v := f_v(\text{Pa}(v), u_v)
   where \text{Pa}(v) denotes the parents of v in \mathcal{G}, and u_v is an exogenous noise variable.
4. P(\mathbf{U}) = \prod_{v \in \mathbf{V}} P(u_v) is a distribution over independent exogenous noise variables, encoding the assumption of no unobserved confounders (causal sufficiency).

The structural equations encode the mechanistic relationships governing the system. For the next state s_{t+1}, the structural equation takes the form:

\boxed{s_{t+1} := f_{\text{sim}}(s_t, a_t; \theta) + \sum_{\delta_i \in \Delta} \gamma_i \cdot \phi_i(s_t, a_t; \delta_i) + \varepsilon_{t+1}}

where:

· f_{\text{sim}} is the nominal simulator dynamics with parameters \theta
· \gamma_i \in \{0,1\} indicates whether mechanism \delta_i is active
· \phi_i is the functional contribution of mechanism \delta_i to the state transition
· \varepsilon_{t+1} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2 I) is isotropic Gaussian noise

The discrepancy nodes \Delta represent distinct physical mechanisms that may be missing or inadequately modeled in the simulator. Examples include:

· \delta_{\text{fric}}: friction modeling errors (hysteresis, Stribeck effects, anisotropic friction)
· \delta_{\text{comp}}: joint and link compliance (deflection under load)
· \delta_{\text{contact}}: contact stiffness and damping (Hertzian contact, restitution)
· \delta_{\text{act}}: actuator dynamics (backlash, torque ripple, saturation)
· \delta_{\text{wear}}: time-varying material properties (fatigue, thermal effects)

2.1.2 Discrepancy Nodes as Latent Causal Variables

A key modeling choice in our framework is the treatment of discrepancy nodes as latent causal variables that are not directly observed but whose effects manifest in the residuals between simulated and real trajectories. This formulation aligns with recent work on causal representation learning for robotics, which seeks to identify latent causal factors from high-dimensional observations.

Each discrepancy node \delta_i is associated with:

· A domain: the subset of state and action variables it affects (e.g., specific joints, contact points)
· An activation function: when and under what conditions the mechanism becomes active
· A functional form: how it contributes to the dynamics

The causal graph \mathcal{G} encodes which discrepancy nodes influence which state variables. For example, a compliance discrepancy \delta_{\text{comp}} may affect only the joint positions under high load, while a friction discrepancy \delta_{\text{fric}} affects velocity damping during contact. Learning this structure from data is the central challenge of causal sim-to-real gap discovery.

2.1.3 Relationship to Concurrent Causal Frameworks

The use of SCMs for robotic dynamics has gained significant traction in 2025-2026. Several recent works provide important context and validation for our approach:

COBRA-PPM (Cannizzaro et al., 2025) combines causal Bayesian networks with probabilistic programming to perform interventional inference for robot manipulation under uncertainty. Their architecture achieves 88.6% prediction accuracy and 94.2% task success on block stacking, and "demonstrates sim2real transfer on a domestic robot, showing effectiveness in handling real-world uncertainty from sensor noise and stochastic actions". Unlike our approach, COBRA-PPM assumes a known causal structure and focuses on probabilistic inference rather than structure discovery.

Causal Correction and Compensation Network (C²-Net) introduces an "interpretable reinforcement learning framework built on the Causal World Model" that "employs causal discovery methods and a Structural Causal Model to learn and formally represent the environment's causal structure, enabling more informed state transition and reward modeling". Our framework extends this line of work by providing formal identifiability guarantees and integrating with differentiable contact dynamics.

Robot Pouring: Modeling and Sim-to-Real Evaluation Using Causal Discovery (Maldonado et al., 2025) represents the closest prior work to our gap discovery formulation. They "use causal analysis methods to identify and evaluate the mismatch between simulation and reality of a robot pouring task" and evaluate "the cause-effect structure of the simulation using a causal discovery algorithm" against real robot data. Their work validates the feasibility of causal discovery for sim-to-real gap identification but is limited to post-hoc analysis rather than online compensation. Our framework builds on this validation while adding online inference, differentiable contact, and safety certification.

Learning Causal Structure Distributions for Robust Planning (Murillo-González et al., 2025) finds that "learning the functional relationships while accounting for the uncertainty about the structural information leads to more robust dynamics models which improves downstream planning". They estimate "a causal structure distribution that is used to sample causal graphs that inform the latent-space representations in an encoder-multidecoder probabilistic model" and validate on manipulators and mobile robots. This work directly motivates our Bayesian model averaging approach over Markov equivalence classes.

Causal World Modeling for Robot Control (Li et al., 2026) introduces LingBot-VA, an autoregressive diffusion framework that "learns frame prediction and policy execution simultaneously" and highlights that "video world models provide the ability to imagine the near future by understanding the causality between actions and visual dynamics". Their model features a "shared latent space, integrating vision and action tokens" and achieves "strong generalizability to novel configurations". However, LingBot-VA's "causality" refers to temporal causal attention (masking future frames for autoregressive prediction), not structural causal discovery. Our framework provides the mechanistic causal reasoning that such world models currently lack.

