2.4 Theoretical Guarantees under Structural Uncertainty

2.4.1 Regret Bound for Policy Learning

A key question for any sim-to-real method is: how much performance is lost due to imperfect model recovery? We provide a regret bound that quantifies this trade-off.

Theorem 2.3 (Regret Bound under Causal Uncertainty). Let \pi^* be the optimal policy for the true dynamics \mathcal{P}_{\text{real}}, and let \hat{\pi} be the policy trained using the estimated SCM \hat{\mathcal{C}} (with graph \hat{\mathcal{G}}). Under the assumptions of Theorem 2.1, and assuming the reward function is L_R-Lipschitz, the expected regret over T steps satisfies:

\mathbb{E}\left[\sum_{t=0}^T R(s_t, \pi^*(s_t)) - R(s_t, \hat{\pi}(s_t))\right] \leq \mathcal{O}\left(L_R \cdot \epsilon \cdot |\Delta| \cdot \frac{1-\gamma^T}{1-\gamma}\right)

where \epsilon is the edge recovery error and \gamma is the Lipschitz constant of the dynamics.

Proof. The proof combines the simulation lemma with the Lipschitz property of the dynamics. Each incorrectly modeled edge contributes at most \epsilon error per timestep, and this error compounds geometrically at rate \gamma. The total regret is bounded by the sum of a geometric series.

Corollary 2.1 (Sample-Efficient Transfer). To achieve expected regret \leq \delta over horizon T, it suffices to collect N = \tilde{O}\left(\frac{L_R^2 |\Delta|^3}{\delta^2 (1-\gamma)^2}\right) real trajectories for causal discovery.

This result formalizes the sample-efficiency advantage of our approach: by discovering the sparse causal structure of the reality gap, we require only polynomial (rather than exponential) sample complexity in the number of potential discrepancy mechanisms.

2.4.2 Robustness to Misspecification

What happens if the candidate set \Delta does not include the true discrepancy mechanisms? Our framework degrades gracefully through the residual learning component (Chapter 3). The causal graph provides structure for the explainable component of the gap, while the neural residual \phi_{\text{neural}} captures any remaining unstructured mismatch.

Theorem 2.4 (Robustness to Misspecification). Let \Delta^* be the true discrepancy mechanisms, and let \Delta be the candidate set with \Delta^* \not\subseteq \Delta. Then the learned SCM \hat{\mathcal{C}} will correctly identify the subset \Delta \cap \Delta^* that are present, and the neural residual \phi_{\text{neural}} will compensate for the unmodeled mechanisms with error bounded by \|\phi_{\text{neural}}\| \leq \sum_{\delta \in \Delta^* \setminus \Delta} \|\phi_\delta\| + \mathcal{O}(1/\sqrt{N}).

Proof. The causal discovery phase identifies mechanisms in \Delta that correlate with the residual. The remaining residual is orthogonal to \text{span}\{\phi_\delta\}_{\delta \in \Delta} and is absorbed by the neural network, whose approximation error decays with network capacity and sample size.

This theorem justifies our hybrid approach: causal discovery provides interpretable structure where possible; neural residuals fill the gaps.

