Chapter 3: Differentiable Hybrid Contact Dynamics with Causal Residuals

The causal SCM developed in Chapter 2 identifies which physical mechanisms are missing from the simulator and how they relate to observable variables. This chapter addresses the complementary challenge: how to compensate for these mechanisms in a physically consistent, real-time deployable manner. We develop a hybrid neuro-analytic dynamics formulation that combines differentiable rigid-body simulation with contact resolution and neural residuals that are structurally constrained by the discovered causal graph. We prove exponential stability under PD control with Lipschitz-bounded residuals, and we demonstrate that causal conditioning improves both sample efficiency and out-of-distribution robustness compared to black-box residual learning.

---

3.1 Differentiable Rigid-Body Dynamics with Contact

3.1.1 Lagrangian Formulation

The dynamics of a rigid-body robotic system with n degrees of freedom can be expressed in standard Lagrangian form:

\boxed{M(q)\ddot{q} + C(q, \dot{q})\dot{q} + g(q) = \tau + \tau_{\text{ext}}}

where:

· q, \dot{q}, \ddot{q} \in \mathbb{R}^n are the generalized positions, velocities, and accelerations
· M(q) \in \mathbb{S}_{++}^n is the symmetric, positive-definite mass matrix
· C(q, \dot{q}) \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n} is the Coriolis and centrifugal force matrix
· g(q) \in \mathbb{R}^n is the gravitational force vector
· \tau \in \mathbb{R}^n is the vector of applied generalized forces (control inputs)
· \tau_{\text{ext}} \in \mathbb{R}^n represents external forces, including contact forces

The mass matrix M(q) and Coriolis matrix C(q, \dot{q}) satisfy the skew-symmetry property: \dot{M}(q) - 2C(q, \dot{q}) is skew-symmetric. This property is essential for stability proofs and energy conservation.

3.1.2 Contact Modeling via Linear Complementarity

Contact forces are modeled using the principle of maximum dissipation and Coulomb friction. Let \lambda \in \mathbb{R}^{3n_c} be the vector of contact forces, where each contact point contributes one normal force and two tangential friction components (n_c total contact points). The contact Jacobian J_c(q) \in \mathbb{R}^{3n_c \times n} maps generalized velocities to contact point velocities:

v_c = J_c(q) \dot{q}

The contact problem can be formulated as a Linear Complementarity Problem (LCP):

0 \leq \lambda \perp A\lambda + b \geq 0

where:

· A \in \mathbb{R}^{3n_c \times 3n_c} is the Delassus operator (inverse inertia in contact space)
· b \in \mathbb{R}^{3n_c} encodes the contact geometry (gap distances) and velocity-dependent terms
· \perp denotes complementarity: for each component i, either \lambda_i = 0 (no contact) or (A\lambda + b)_i = 0 (contact with non-penetration)

The LCP formulation enforces:

· Non-penetration: \phi(q) \geq 0 (signed distance)
· Complementary: \lambda_n \geq 0, \lambda_n \cdot \phi(q) = 0
· Friction cone: \|\lambda_t\| \leq \mu \lambda_n (Coulomb friction)

3.1.3 Differentiability of LCP Solutions

To enable gradient-based optimization, we require derivatives of the LCP solution with respect to problem parameters (state, action, and simulator parameters). The implicit function theorem, applied to the active constraint set, yields:

Theorem 3.1 (LCP Gradient). Let \lambda^* be a solution to the LCP 0 \leq \lambda \perp A\lambda + b \geq 0, and let \mathcal{I} = \{i : \lambda_i^* = 0\} be the inactive set and \mathcal{A} = \{i : \lambda_i^* > 0\} be the active set. Under strict complementarity (\lambda_i^* > 0 \iff (A\lambda^* + b)_i = 0), the derivative with respect to parameter \theta is:

\frac{\partial \lambda^*}{\partial \theta} = - \begin{bmatrix} A_{\mathcal{A}\mathcal{A}} \\ I_{\mathcal{I}\mathcal{I}} \end{bmatrix}^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} \frac{\partial b_{\mathcal{A}}}{\partial \theta} \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}

Proof. On the active set, (A\lambda^* + b)_{\mathcal{A}} = 0. Differentiating yields A_{\mathcal{A}\mathcal{A}} \frac{\partial \lambda_{\mathcal{A}}}{\partial \theta} + \frac{\partial b_{\mathcal{A}}}{\partial \theta} = 0. On the inactive set, \lambda_{\mathcal{I}} = 0 so \frac{\partial \lambda_{\mathcal{I}}}{\partial \theta} = 0. The result follows by solving the linear system.

In practice, strict complementarity may be violated. Recent differentiable contact simulators address this through:

· Smoothed complementarity: Replace the LCP with a smooth approximation (e.g., using softplus functions)
· Implicit differentiation with regularization: Add a small diagonal term to A for numerical stability

Differentiable contact refinement enables "smooth, gradient-based optimization of contact parameters, geometry, and forces" across the entire simulation pipeline. Core methods include penalty-based soft contact models, LCP-based hard contact formulations, and geometric regularization to ensure analytic gradients throughout the simulation pipeline. Our implementation uses the CVXPYLayers library, which provides differentiable convex optimization layers including LCP solvers.

3.1.4 Certified Gradient-Based Contact-Rich Manipulation

A recent breakthrough in differentiable contact simulation is the work of Li and Chou (2026) on Certified Gradient-Based Contact-Rich Manipulation via Smoothing-Error Reachable Tubes:

"Gradient-based methods can efficiently optimize controllers using physical priors and differentiable simulators, but contact-rich manipulation remains challenging due to discontinuous or vanishing gradients from hybrid contact dynamics. Smoothing the dynamics yields continuous gradients, but the resulting model mismatch can cause controller failures when executed on real systems. We address this trade-off by planning with smoothed dynamics while explicitly quantifying and compensating for the induced errors, providing formal guarantees of constraint satisfaction and goal reachability on the true hybrid dynamics."

Their method smooths both contact dynamics and geometry via a differentiable simulator based on convex optimization, enabling characterization of "the discrepancy from the true dynamics as a set-valued deviation" which "constrains the optimization of time-varying affine feedback policies through analytical bounds on the system's reachable set". This is the "first certifiable gradient-based policy synthesis method for contact-rich manipulation".

Our framework builds on this foundation by adding causal structure to the residual modeling, enabling tighter uncertainty bounds and more efficient safety certification (Chapter 4).

