3.2 Hybrid Neuro-Analytic Dynamics with Causal Residuals

3.2.1 Formulation

We augment the analytical rigid-body dynamics with a neural residual term that is structurally constrained by the discovered causal graph:

\boxed{M(q)\ddot{q} + C(q, \dot{q})\dot{q} + g(q) = J_c^\top \lambda + \phi_{\text{neural}}(q, \dot{q}, \lambda; \mathcal{C}) + \tau}

where:

· \lambda solves the differentiable LCP described in Section 3.1
· \phi_{\text{neural}}: \mathbb{R}^n \times \mathbb{R}^n \times \mathbb{R}^{3n_c} \times \mathcal{C} \to \mathbb{R}^n is a neural network
· \mathcal{C} is the discovered causal graph (Chapter 2)

The key innovation is causal masking: the neural network \phi_{\text{neural}} is constrained such that its functional connectivity reflects the causal graph \mathcal{C}. Specifically, if the causal graph indicates that discrepancy node \delta_k affects only state variables in the set \mathcal{S}_k \subset \mathbf{S}, then the output of \phi_{\text{neural}} for dimensions outside \mathcal{S}_k is forced to zero.

Definition 3.1 (Causally Masked Neural Residual). Let W_{\text{out}} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times d} be the output weight matrix of \phi_{\text{neural}} and let M_{\mathcal{C}} \in \{0,1\}^{n \times n} be the causal mask matrix, where (M_{\mathcal{C}})_{ij} = 1 if there exists a directed path from discrepancy node \delta_j to state variable s_i in the causal graph \mathcal{G}, and 0 otherwise. The causally masked residual is:

\phi_{\text{neural}}(x; \mathcal{C}) = (M_{\mathcal{C}} \odot W_{\text{out}}) \cdot h(x) + b

where h(x) is the hidden representation, and \odot denotes element-wise multiplication.

This structural constraint provides three benefits:

1. Sample Efficiency: Parameters are shared only where causally justified, reducing effective dimension
2. Interpretability: Each non-zero weight corresponds to a specific causal mechanism
3. OOD Robustness: The model cannot learn spurious correlations that violate causal structure

3.2.2 Contact-Aware Neural Dynamics

Our formulation aligns with the emerging field of contact-aware neural dynamics models, which are "a class of machine learning approaches designed to capture, predict, and leverage the discontinuous, non-smooth behavior that arises in physical systems involving contacts, impacts, and friction—domains where classical and naive neural dynamics models often fail".

These models explicitly incorporate contact information into the dynamic prediction process, "thereby enabling accurate simulation, control, and policy optimization for contact-rich robotic tasks". The mathematical formulation of residual correction models takes the form:

s_{t+1} = S_{\text{sim}}(s_t, a_t) + \Delta_\theta(s_t, a_t, c_t)

where c_t is a binary contact observation from tactile sensors.

Our causally masked residual extends this approach by conditioning not just on binary contact but on the full LCP solution \lambda and the causal graph \mathcal{C}, enabling more nuanced, physically grounded corrections.

3.2.3 Integration with the Causal Graph

The causal graph \mathcal{C} discovered in Chapter 2 provides the mask M_{\mathcal{C}} that structures \phi_{\text{neural}}. The integration proceeds as follows:

1. Causal Discovery: Run Algorithm 2.1 on \mathcal{D}_{\text{real}} to obtain posterior P(\mathcal{G} \mid \mathcal{D})
2. Graph Selection: Sample K graphs from the posterior for Bayesian model averaging
3. Mask Construction: For each sampled graph \mathcal{G}_k, construct causal mask M_{\mathcal{G}_k}
4. Ensemble Training: Train K neural residual models, each with its corresponding mask
5. Inference: Average predictions across the ensemble: \phi_{\text{neural}}(x) = \frac{1}{K} \sum_{k=1}^K \phi_k(x; \mathcal{G}_k)

This Bayesian ensemble approach propagates structural uncertainty through to the dynamics predictions, improving robustness when the causal graph is imperfectly recovered.

