Few-Shot Neural Differentiable Simulator (Huang et al., 2026) is particularly relevant: it "combines the physical consistency of analytical formulations with the representational capacity of graph neural network (GNN)-based models" and uses "a mesh-based GNN that implicitly models rigid-body forward dynamics" with "surrogate gradients for collision detection, achieving full differentiability". Their approach achieves "improved simulation fidelity with minimal supervision". However, their GNN structure is learned from data without causal grounding, whereas our masking is explicitly derived from discovered causal mechanisms.

