3.4 Forward Pass Algorithm

3.4.1 Algorithm Description

Algorithm 3.1 details the forward pass of the hybrid dynamics model, which computes the next state given current state and action.

```
Algorithm 3.1: Causal Hybrid Dynamics Forward Pass
───────────────────────────────────────────────────
Input: Current state (q, q̇), action τ_cmd,
       Causal graph posterior P(𝒢 | 𝒟),
       Neural residual ensemble {ϕ_k}_{k=1}^K
Output: Next acceleration q̈, contact forces λ,
        Safety flag

1. // Step 1: Compute nominal terms
2. M ← MassMatrix(q)
3. C ← CoriolisMatrix(q, q̇)
4. g ← GravityVector(q)
5. J_c ← ContactJacobian(q)
6.
7. // Step 2: Solve LCP for contact forces
8. A ← J_c M^{-1} J_c^\top
9. b ← J_c M^{-1}(τ_cmd - C q̇ - g) + J̇_c q̇
10. λ ← SolveLCP(A, b)  // Differentiable LCP solver
11.
12. // Step 3: Compute causally masked residual
13. φ ← 0
14. for k = 1 to K:
15.   𝒢_k ← Sample(P(𝒢 | 𝒟))
16.   M_k ← CausalMask(𝒢_k)
17.   φ ← φ + (1/K) · ϕ_k(q, q̇, λ; M_k)
18.
19. // Step 4: Compute acceleration
20. τ_total ← τ_cmd - C q̇ - g + J_c^\top λ + φ
21. q̈ ← M^{-1} τ_total
22.
23. // Step 5: Safety check
24. if ‖φ‖ > L_max or λ violates friction cone:
25.   safety_flag ← True
26. else:
27.   safety_flag ← False
28.
29. return q̈, λ, safety_flag
```

3.4.2 Differentiable LCP Solver Details

The SolveLCP function in Line 10 is implemented using CVXPYLayers, which provides differentiable convex optimization layers. The LCP is reformulated as a quadratic program:

\min_{\lambda \geq 0} \frac{1}{2}\lambda^\top A\lambda + b^\top \lambda

The KKT conditions of this QP are exactly the LCP conditions. The solver returns both the optimal \lambda^* and the gradients \partial\lambda^*/\partial A and \partial\lambda^*/\partial b via implicit differentiation.

3.4.3 Computational Complexity and Real-Time Feasibility

Theorem 3.3 (Real-Time Forward Pass Complexity). The forward pass of Algorithm 3.1 has computational complexity:

T(n, n_c, K) = O(n^3 + n_c^3 + K \cdot d_\phi)

where n is the DOF, n_c is the number of contact points, K is the ensemble size, and d_\phi is the neural network inference cost.

For typical robotic systems with n \leq 50, n_c \leq 10, K = 5, and a small MLP (d_\phi \approx 10^4 FLOPs), the forward pass requires:

· Mass matrix inversion: O(n^3) \approx 125,000 FLOPs (Cholesky)
· LCP solve: O(n_c^3) \approx 1,000 FLOPs
· Neural inference: K \cdot d_\phi \approx 50,000 FLOPs

Total: < 200,000 FLOPs per timestep. On a Jetson Orin (275 TOPS), this is < 1 \mu\text{s} of compute time. Memory access and synchronization dominate; empirical measurements show < 2 \text{ms} end-to-end latency at 100 Hz control frequency.

