3.5 Training and Calibration

3.5.1 Loss Function

The neural residual \phi_{\text{neural}} is trained to minimize the prediction error on the real dataset \mathcal{D}_{\text{real}}:

\mathcal{L}(\phi) = \frac{1}{N T} \sum_{i=1}^N \sum_{t=0}^{T-1} \|s_{t+1}^{(i)} - \hat{s}_{t+1}^{(i)}\|^2 + \lambda_{\text{reg}} \|\phi\|_{\text{Lip}}^2

where:

· \hat{s}_{t+1} = \text{ForwardPass}(s_t, a_t; \phi) is the predicted next state
· \|\phi\|_{\text{Lip}} is an estimate of the Lipschitz constant of \phi (e.g., via spectral normalization)
· \lambda_{\text{reg}} is a regularization weight enforcing the stability condition

3.5.2 Spectral Normalization for Lipschitz Control

To ensure the Lipschitz condition L < \lambda_{\min}(K_d)/\|J_c\|^2, we employ spectral normalization (Miyato et al., 2018) on the weight matrices of \phi_{\text{neural}}. Each linear layer is parameterized as:

W = \frac{W_{\text{raw}}}{\sigma(W_{\text{raw}})} \cdot c

where \sigma(W) is the spectral norm (largest singular value) and c is a scaling factor chosen to satisfy the Lipschitz bound.

3.5.3 Few-Shot Calibration

A key advantage of our causal masking approach is sample efficiency. The structural constraints from the causal graph dramatically reduce the effective parameter count, enabling calibration with very few real trajectories. Empirical results (reported in Chapter 7) show:

· 5 trajectories: 60% of asymptotic performance
· 10 trajectories: 85% of asymptotic performance
· 15 trajectories: 95% of asymptotic performance

This few-shot capability aligns with recent work on "few-shot real-to-sim" methods that "calibrate analytical simulators to generate large-scale synthetic datasets that capture diverse contact interactions". Our causal approach further improves sample efficiency by focusing learning on causally relevant dimensions.

