Chapter 4: Conformal Causal Safety Filtering

The previous chapters established a framework for discovering the causal structure of the sim-to-real gap (Chapter 2) and compensating for it through causally constrained hybrid dynamics (Chapter 3). However, even with perfect causal discovery and expressive neural residuals, there remains epistemic uncertainty—the model may be imperfect due to finite calibration data, unobserved confounding, or distributional shift. In safety-critical robotics applications, deploying a policy without formal guarantees on its behavior is unacceptable.

This chapter develops the third pillar of CausalSim++: Conformal Causal Safety Filtering. We unify causal residual prediction with split-conformal inference to yield finite-sample, distribution-free safety certificates. Crucially, we prove that coverage guarantees hold even when the causal graph is recovered only up to Markov equivalence, and we show that causal conditioning reduces prediction set volume compared to black-box conformal approaches. The safety filter operates in real time, triggering a provably safe fallback controller when the conformal prediction set intersects an unsafe region.

