4.1 The Safety Certification Problem in Sim-to-Real Transfer

4.1.1 Problem Statement

We consider a robotic system governed by the true dynamics \mathcal{P}_{\text{real}} (unknown at deployment time) and equipped with a learned policy \pi trained in simulation using the causally augmented dynamics model from Chapter 3. Before deploying \pi on hardware, we collect a small calibration dataset of real-world trajectories:

\mathcal{D}_{\text{cal}} = \{\tau_1, \dots, \tau_{N_{\text{cal}}}\}, \quad \tau_i = (s_0^{(i)}, a_0^{(i)}, s_1^{(i)}, \dots, s_T^{(i)})

These trajectories are collected under a safe exploration policy (e.g., a conservative PD controller or human teleoperation). The goal is to construct a safety monitor that, at each timestep during deployment, decides whether the predicted future state from the learned policy is likely to violate safety constraints. If a violation is predicted, the monitor must trigger a fallback controller that is provably safe.

Definition 4.1 (Safe Set). The safe set \mathcal{S}_{\text{safe}} \subset \mathcal{S} is the set of states satisfying all safety constraints (e.g., joint limits, obstacle avoidance, force/torque bounds). The unsafe set is \mathcal{S}_{\text{unsafe}} = \mathcal{S} \setminus \mathcal{S}_{\text{safe}}.

Definition 4.2 (Safety Monitor). A safety monitor is a function \mu: \mathcal{H}_t \to \{0, 1\}, where \mathcal{H}_t = (o_0, a_0, \dots, o_t) is the observation-action history. If \mu(\mathcal{H}_t) = 1, the learned policy action is executed; if \mu(\mathcal{H}_t) = 0, a fallback safe controller is activated.

Objective: Design \mu such that, with user-specified probability 1-\alpha, the system never enters \mathcal{S}_{\text{unsafe}} during deployment, without making parametric assumptions about the dynamics mismatch.

4.1.2 Why Existing Methods Fall Short

Traditional approaches to safe learning in robotics include:

· Robust Control: Provides worst-case guarantees but is overly conservative when the true uncertainty is smaller than the assumed bounds.
· Bayesian Methods: Quantify uncertainty via posterior distributions but rely on correct prior specification and Gaussian assumptions that are often violated in contact-rich robotics.
· Reachability Analysis: Computes exact reachable sets but scales poorly to high-dimensional systems with learned components.
· Barrier Functions: Guarantee safety given a valid CBF, but constructing a valid CBF for general nonlinear systems with unknown dynamics is challenging.

Recent work on Conformal Prediction for Robotics offers a compelling alternative: it provides finite-sample, distribution-free coverage guarantees without assumptions on the underlying distribution beyond exchangeability. However, standard conformal prediction treats the prediction model as a black box and constructs uncertainty sets based on raw residuals. In the sim-to-real setting, this leads to unnecessarily large prediction sets because the residual contains both reducible (structural) and irreducible (noise) components. Our causal framework enables us to separate these components, yielding tighter, more informative prediction sets.

4.1.3 Relationship to Concurrent Work on Conformal Safety

The application of conformal prediction to robotics safety has advanced rapidly in 2025-2026. Key works include:

· Staggered Integral Online Conformal Prediction (Angelopoulos et al., 2026): Extends conformal prediction to multi-step coverage for dynamics adaptation, providing "long-run coverage guarantees, resulting in long-run safety when synthesized with safety-critical controllers". The method handles non-exchangeable data through online adaptation.
· Conformal Prediction with Reachability Analysis (Hashemi et al., 2026): Combines "finite-sample, distribution-free guarantees with set-based reachability to certify system safety". They use conformal prediction to quantify model error, then propagate this uncertainty through reachability analysis.
· Safe Probabilistic Planning using Conformal Risk Control (Muthali et al., 2026): Quantifies "prediction errors in CBF safety values and establishes formal guarantees on the probability of constraint satisfaction" using conformal risk control.
· Certified Gradient-Based Contact-Rich Manipulation (Li & Chou, 2026): Provides "formal guarantees of constraint satisfaction and goal reachability on the true hybrid dynamics" by quantifying smoothing-induced errors through reachable tubes.

Our contribution, Conformal Causal Safety Filtering, differs from these approaches in one crucial aspect: we condition the uncertainty quantification on the causal structure of the sim-to-real gap. By computing nonconformity scores on causally corrected residuals, we obtain prediction sets that are both tighter (smaller volume) and more interpretable (uncertainty can be attributed to specific causal mechanisms). Furthermore, we prove that coverage guarantees hold even when the causal graph is imperfectly recovered—a robustness property essential for practical deployment.

