4.2 Conformal Prediction Preliminaries

We briefly review the foundations of split-conformal prediction, establishing notation and key theorems. For a comprehensive treatment, see Angelopoulos & Bates (2023).

4.2.1 Exchangeability and Nonconformity Scores

Definition 4.3 (Exchangeability). A sequence of random variables Z_1, \dots, Z_N is exchangeable if for any permutation \sigma of \{1, \dots, N\}, the joint distribution satisfies:

(Z_1, \dots, Z_N) \stackrel{d}{=} (Z_{\sigma(1)}, \dots, Z_{\sigma(N)})

Independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) sequences are exchangeable, but exchangeability is a weaker condition that allows for certain dependencies (e.g., sampling without replacement).

Definition 4.4 (Nonconformity Score). A nonconformity score s: \mathcal{X} \times \mathcal{Y} \to \mathbb{R} measures how "atypical" a prediction is relative to observed data. Larger scores indicate poorer agreement between prediction and outcome. Common choices include:

· Absolute residual: s(x, y) = \|\hat{y}(x) - y\|
· Normalized residual: s(x, y) = \|\hat{y}(x) - y\| / \hat{\sigma}(x)
· Mahalanobis distance: s(x, y) = (\hat{y}(x) - y)^\top \hat{\Sigma}^{-1}(x) (\hat{y}(x) - y)

4.2.2 Split-Conformal Prediction

Split-conformal prediction divides the available data into a training set (used to fit the prediction model) and a calibration set (used to calibrate the prediction intervals). This separation avoids overfitting and ensures valid coverage without assumptions on the model.

Algorithm 4.1 (Split-Conformal Prediction)

```
Input: Calibration data {(X_i, Y_i)}_{i=1}^N,
       Prediction model f̂, nonconformity score s,
       Target coverage 1-α
Output: Prediction set function Ĉ(·)

1. Compute calibration scores:
   s_i = s(X_i, Y_i) for i = 1, …, N

2. Compute empirical quantile:
   q̂ = Quantile({s_1, …, s_N, ∞}, ⌈(1-α)(N+1)⌉ / N)

3. Define prediction set:
   Ĉ(X) = {y : s(X, y) ≤ q̂}

4. return Ĉ
```

Theorem 4.1 (Split-Conformal Coverage Guarantee). If the calibration data (X_1, Y_1), \dots, (X_N, Y_N) and the test point (X_{N+1}, Y_{N+1}) are exchangeable, then:

\mathbb{P}(Y_{N+1} \in \hat{C}(X_{N+1})) \geq 1-\alpha

The probability is taken over the randomness in the calibration and test data.

Proof. By exchangeability, the rank of s_{N+1} among \{s_1, \dots, s_{N+1}\} is uniformly distributed. Therefore, the probability that s_{N+1} exceeds the (1-\alpha) quantile of the calibration scores is at most \alpha. ∎

Remark 4.1 (Finite-Sample Validity). The guarantee holds for any sample size N, any prediction model \hat{f}, and any score function s. This distribution-free property is the key advantage of conformal prediction over Bayesian or frequentist alternatives.

4.2.3 Conformal Prediction for Time Series

The exchangeability assumption is violated for time series data due to temporal dependencies. Recent work has extended conformal prediction to this setting:

· Block-Conformal: Group observations into blocks and treat blocks as exchangeable units.
· Online Conformal: Update the quantile estimate sequentially using online gradient descent, providing long-run coverage guarantees for arbitrary non-exchangeable sequences (Gibbs & Candès, 2021).
· Conformal PID Control: Use a PID controller on the quantile level to maintain coverage despite distribution shifts (Angelopoulos et al., 2023).

For our trajectory-based safety monitor, we adopt the trajectory exchangeability assumption: entire trajectories are assumed exchangeable across different calibration runs. This is reasonable when each trajectory is collected under similar conditions (same environment, same safe exploration policy). We discuss relaxation of this assumption in Section 4.6.

