Chapter 5: Perception-to-Causal-State via Causal Representation Learning

The preceding chapters assumed access to the true state s_t \in \mathcal{S} for causal discovery, dynamics prediction, and safety monitoring. In real-world robotic deployment, we observe only high-dimensional sensory data—RGB images, depth maps, proprioceptive readings—not the underlying physical state. This chapter bridges the perception gap through Causal Representation Learning (CRL). We develop an encoder that maps observations to a disentangled causal latent space, enabling the entire CausalSim++ pipeline to operate directly from pixels. The encoder is pretrained in simulation (where ground-truth causal variables are available) and finetuned on real data using interventional consistency losses. We provide theoretical justification for identifiability of causal variables from interventions and design a training procedure that preserves the causal structure necessary for downstream safety guarantees.

---

5.1 The Perception-to-State Gap

5.1.1 Problem Statement

In simulation, we have full access to the ground-truth state s_t (joint positions, velocities, contact forces, etc.). In reality, we only have access to observations o_t \in \mathcal{O} (e.g., o_t \in \mathbb{R}^{H \times W \times 3} for RGB images). The observation function \Omega_{\text{real}}: \mathcal{S} \to \mathcal{O} is unknown and potentially stochastic. We must learn a mapping from observations to a latent representation that is sufficient for causal reasoning and control.

Definition 5.1 (Causal Sufficiency of Representation). A representation z = h_\psi(o) is causally sufficient if there exists a mapping \rho: \mathcal{Z} \to \mathcal{S} such that the causal relationships among z are isomorphic to those among s. That is, intervening on a causal variable in \mathcal{Z} corresponds to the same intervention in \mathcal{S}.

Objective: Learn an encoder h_\psi: \mathcal{O} \to \mathcal{Z} and a dynamics model in the latent space such that the CausalSim++ framework (causal discovery, hybrid dynamics, conformal safety) can be applied directly to z_t.

5.1.2 Challenges and Why Standard Representation Learning Fails

Standard representation learning methods (e.g., VAEs, contrastive learning) learn embeddings that are useful for reconstruction or prediction but do not guarantee causal disentanglement. Without explicit causal structure, the latent variables may be entangled in ways that:

· Confound causal discovery (spurious correlations)
· Violate the independent mechanisms assumption
· Fail to transfer across domains (sim-to-real)

Causal Representation Learning (CRL) addresses this by explicitly modeling the causal generative process and using interventions to identify true causal variables.

5.1.3 Related Work: CRL for Robotics

The application of CRL to robotics is nascent but rapidly advancing. Key works include:

· ROPES (Jiang et al., NeurIPS 2025): "Comparing distributions induced by interventions enables identifiability" of robot pose and other controllable variables from raw images. They demonstrate that "variables that undergo variations via interventions can be identified" and validate on pose estimation tasks. The authors note a "substantial gap remains between theory and real-world practice."
· Causal-JEPA (C-JEPA) (Jabri et al., Feb 2026): Integrates "object-centric representations with a Joint Embedding Predictive Architecture to improve visual reasoning and robotic planning" through object-level latent masking. While not fully causally disentangled, it demonstrates that object-centric inductive biases improve causal reasoning.
· HCLSM (Rakelly et al., March 2026): Learns "hierarchical causal latent state machines" that combine object-centric decomposition with "causal structure learning through graph neural network interaction patterns." The hierarchical structure captures multi-timescale causal dynamics.
· Learning Latent Causal Factors from Contact-Rich Assembly (Zhang et al., 2025): Identifies "five robotic priors" for learning state representations that "greatly improve generalization in reinforcement learning" for contact-rich tasks.

Our approach builds on these foundations, specifically tailoring CRL to the sim-to-real setting where we have access to a fully observable simulator for pretraining and interventional data from real-world calibration.

---

5.2 Causal Representation Learning Formulation

5.2.1 Generative Model

We posit a generative model for observations:

\begin{aligned}
s_t &\sim P(s_t \mid s_{t-1}, a_{t-1}; \mathcal{C}) \quad \text{(causal dynamics)} \\
o_t &\sim P(o_t \mid s_t; \phi) \quad \text{(observation model)}
\end{aligned}

The causal dynamics P(s_t \mid s_{t-1}, a_{t-1}; \mathcal{C}) is exactly the SCM from Chapter 2. The observation model P(o_t \mid s_t) is a complex, nonlinear mapping (e.g., rendering engine in simulation, real camera physics in reality).

The goal of CRL is to learn an encoder h_\psi: \mathcal{O} \to \mathcal{Z} that inverts the observation model up to a causal isomorphism: there exists a bijection \rho: \mathcal{Z} \to \mathcal{S} such that \rho(z_t) = s_t and the causal graph on \mathcal{Z} is identical to \mathcal{C}.

5.2.2 Identifiability from Interventions

Recent theoretical results in CRL establish that causal variables can be identified up to permutation and element-wise transformations if we have access to interventional data.

Theorem 5.1 (Identifiability of Causal Variables from Interventions, adapted from Brehmer et al., 2022). Assume:

1. The true latent causal variables s \in \mathbb{R}^n follow a nonlinear SCM with independent noise.
2. The observation function o = g(s) is a smooth, injective mapping with a smooth inverse.
3. We observe data under multiple interventions on subsets of the causal variables, where each intervention changes the conditional distribution of the intervened variable.

Then the latent causal variables are identifiable up to permutation and element-wise invertible transformations.

Proof sketch. Interventions break the symmetries that make nonlinear ICA non-identifiable. By comparing the distribution of observations under different interventions, we can identify the independent mechanisms and recover the true causal variables. For a full proof, see Brehmer et al. (2022) and von Kügelgen et al. (2023).

In our setting, actions a_t serve as perfect interventions on the action node in the causal graph. Additionally, we can perform targeted physical interventions during calibration (e.g., adding known payloads, changing surface materials) to further constrain identifiability.

5.2.3 Semi-Supervised CRL with Simulation Pretraining

A key practical insight is that we do not need to perform fully unsupervised CRL from scratch on real data. We can leverage the simulator—where we have full access to ground-truth causal variables—to pretrain the encoder, then finetune on real data with limited supervision.

This intervention-supervised approach significantly reduces the sample complexity and improves robustness. The training procedure consists of three phases:

Phase 1: Simulator Pretraining. Train encoder h_\psi and decoder d_\xi on simulated observation-state pairs (o_t^{\text{sim}}, s_t^{\text{sim}}) using a reconstruction loss:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{recon}} = \mathbb{E}_{(o, s) \sim \mathcal{D}_{\text{sim}}} \left[ \|d_\xi(h_\psi(o)) - o\|^2 + \|h_\psi(o) - s\|^2 \right]

The second term encourages the latent space to align with the true physical state, ensuring causal interpretability.

Phase 2: Causal Consistency Regularization. Augment the training with a causal consistency loss that enforces the learned latent dynamics to match the true causal SCM:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{causal}} = \mathbb{E}_{(s_t, a_t, s_{t+1}) \sim \mathcal{D}_{\text{sim}}} \left[ \| \hat{f}_{\mathcal{C}}(h_\psi(o_t), a_t) - h_\psi(o_{t+1}) \|^2 \right]

where \hat{f}_{\mathcal{C}} is the causally augmented dynamics model from Chapter 3.

Phase 3: Real-World Finetuning. On the real calibration dataset \mathcal{D}_{\text{cal}} (which includes observations and actions, but not ground-truth states), finetune the encoder using:

· Cycle consistency: \|h_\psi(o_t^{\text{real}}) - h_\psi(d_\xi(h_\psi(o_t^{\text{real}})))\|^2
· Interventional consistency: For pairs of observations before and after a known intervention (e.g., a specific action sequence), the change in latent space should match the predicted change from the causal model.

---

5.3 CRL Encoder Architecture

5.3.1 Network Design

The encoder h_\psi is a convolutional neural network (e.g., ResNet-50) that maps an image o_t \in \mathbb{R}^{H \times W \times 3} to a latent vector z_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d_z}. The latent dimension d_z is chosen to match the dimensionality of the causal state variables (e.g., joint positions, velocities). The architecture includes:

· Input: RGB image (optionally concatenated with depth)
· Backbone: ResNet-50 pretrained on ImageNet, with final layers replaced
· Output heads:
  · z_t^{\text{phys}}: Physical state variables (positions, velocities)
  · z_t^{\delta}: Discrepancy state estimates (latent representations of unmodeled mechanisms)
  · \Sigma_t: Uncertainty estimate (diagonal covariance for Mahalanobis distance)

The decoder d_\xi is a transposed convolutional network that reconstructs the input image from z_t, used during pretraining for regularization.

5.3.2 Causal Masking in Latent Space

A crucial design choice is to enforce that the latent dynamics respect the causal graph \mathcal{C}. We apply the same causal masking technique from Chapter 3 to the latent transition model:

\hat{z}_{t+1} = f_{\text{sim}}(z_t^{\text{phys}}, a_t) + (M_{\mathcal{C}} \odot W) \cdot h(z_t) + b

This ensures that the learned latent dynamics are causally consistent with the discovered SCM.

---

5.4 Training Algorithm

Algorithm 5.1 (Intervention-Supervised CRL for CausalSim++)

```
Input: Simulator with ground-truth states 𝒟_sim,
       Real calibration data 𝒟_cal (observations + actions),
       Causal graph posterior P(𝒢 | 𝒟_cal) (from Ch. 2)
Output: Trained encoder h_ψ

1. // Phase 1: Simulator Pretraining
2. for epoch = 1 to E_sim:
3.   Sample batch (o, s) from 𝒟_sim
4.   z ← h_ψ(o)
5.   ô ← d_ξ(z)
6.   ℒ ← ‖ô - o‖^2 + λ_sim ‖z - s‖^2
7.   Update ψ, ξ via gradient descent

8. // Phase 2: Causal Consistency
9. for epoch = 1 to E_causal:
10.  Sample transition (o_t, a_t, o_{t+1}, s_t, s_{t+1}) from 𝒟_sim
11.  z_t, z_{t+1} ← h_ψ(o_t), h_ψ(o_{t+1})
12.  ẑ_{t+1} ← f_{sim+𝒞}(z_t, a_t)  // Causal dynamics model
13.  ℒ_c ← ‖ẑ_{t+1} - z_{t+1}‖^2 + ‖z_t - s_t‖^2
14.  Update ψ via gradient descent

15. // Phase 3: Real-World Finetuning
16. for epoch = 1 to E_real:
17.  Sample batch from 𝒟_cal: (o_t, a_t, o_{t+1})
18.  z_t, z_{t+1} ← h_ψ(o_t), h_ψ(o_{t+1})
19.  ẑ_{t+1} ← f_{sim+𝒞}(z_t, a_t)
20.  ℒ ← ‖ẑ_{t+1} - z_{t+1}‖^2 + λ_cycle ‖h_ψ(d_ξ(z_t)) - z_t‖^2
21.  Update ψ via gradient descent (decoder ξ frozen)

22. return h_ψ
```

5.4.1 Domain Adaptation Techniques

To handle the visual domain gap between simulation and reality, we employ standard domain adaptation techniques:

· Input-level: Random convolutions, color jitter, Gaussian blur during pretraining
· Feature-level: Gradient reversal layer (Ganin et al., 2016) to learn domain-invariant features
· Output-level: Cycle-consistency loss to ensure latent space alignment

These techniques have been extensively validated for sim-to-real transfer in vision-based robotics (e.g., James et al., 2019; Tobin et al., 2017).

---

5.5 Integration with CausalSim++ Pipeline

With the CRL encoder in place, the full CausalSim++ pipeline operates entirely in the learned latent space \mathcal{Z}:

1. Observation to Latent: z_t = h_\psi(o_t)
2. Causal SCM Inference: Run Algorithm 2.1 on latent trajectories to update belief over \mathcal{C}
3. Hybrid Dynamics: Predict \hat{z}_{t+1} using Algorithm 3.1 with causally masked residual
4. Conformal Safety: Compute nonconformity score s_t = \|z_{t+1}^{\text{real}} - \hat{z}_{t+1}\|_{\Sigma}, check against quantile
5. Policy: \pi(z_t, \hat{\mathcal{C}}) outputs action a_t

The safety guarantees from Chapter 4 extend to the latent space if the encoder is Lipschitz continuous and the latent dynamics are consistent with the true dynamics.

Proposition 5.1 (Coverage in Latent Space). Let h_\psi be L_h-Lipschitz and invertible on the support of the data. If the conformal coverage guarantee holds in state space (Theorem 4.2), then it holds in latent space with coverage probability at least 1-\alpha - \mathcal{O}(\epsilon_h), where \epsilon_h is the encoder reconstruction error.

Proof sketch. The encoder's reconstruction error introduces a bounded perturbation to the nonconformity scores. By the Lipschitz property, this perturbation is bounded, and the conformal quantile can be inflated to account for it. See Appendix B for full derivation.

