Chapter 6: System Integration and Real-Time Deployment

The preceding chapters have developed the three theoretical pillars of CausalSim++: causal SCM discovery (Chapter 2), causally constrained hybrid dynamics (Chapter 3), and conformal causal safety filtering (Chapter 4), along with the perception bridge via CRL (Chapter 5). This chapter integrates these components into a unified, real-time deployable software architecture. We describe the end-to-end data flow, the modular software design, the computational optimizations for edge deployment, and the interfaces between components. While this dissertation does not include physical experiments, we provide a detailed design specification that enables future implementation and validation.

---

6.1 System Overview

CausalSim++ is designed as a modular, real-time pipeline that runs on a robotic edge compute platform (e.g., NVIDIA Jetson Orin). The system operates at a fixed control frequency (typically 50-100 Hz for manipulation tasks) and processes the following loop at each timestep:

1. Perception: Capture observation o_t (RGB image, depth, proprioception)
2. CRL Encoding: Map o_t to latent causal state z_t = h_\psi(o_t)
3. Causal Inference: Update belief over causal graph P(\mathcal{C} \mid \mathcal{H}_t) (asynchronous, lower frequency)
4. Dynamics Prediction: Predict \hat{z}_{t+1} using causal hybrid dynamics
5. Policy Evaluation: Compute policy action a_t^\pi = \pi(z_t, \hat{\mathcal{C}})
6. Conformal Safety Check: Construct prediction set \hat{C}_t and verify \hat{C}_t \cap \mathcal{Z}_{\text{unsafe}} = \emptyset
7. Action Execution: Send safe action a_t to low-level controller

The pipeline is illustrated in Figure 6.1 (to be rendered in final thesis).

---

6.2 Software Architecture

6.2.1 Modular Component Design

CausalSim++ is organized into six primary modules, each implemented as a separate ROS 2 node or Python class with well-defined interfaces:

Module 1: Perception Node (CRL Encoder)

· Input: Camera image (and optionally depth), proprioceptive sensors
· Output: Latent state z_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d_z}, uncertainty \Sigma_t
· Implementation: PyTorch model exported to TensorRT for inference
· Frequency: Camera frame rate (30-60 Hz)

Module 2: Causal Inference Engine

· Input: History of (z_t, a_t, z_{t+1}) from real calibration data
· Output: Posterior over causal graphs P(\mathcal{C} \mid \mathcal{D}), updated asynchronously
· Implementation: Python with JAX for NOTEARS optimization
· Frequency: Offline or low-frequency online updates (e.g., once per minute)

Module 3: Differentiable Dynamics Core

· Input: Current latent state z_t, action a_t, causal mask M_{\mathcal{C}}
· Output: Predicted next state \hat{z}_{t+1}, contact forces \lambda, safety flag
· Implementation: Warp (NVIDIA) for rigid-body dynamics, CVXPYLayers for LCP
· Frequency: Control loop rate (100 Hz)

Module 4: Policy Module

· Input: Latent state z_t, causal graph sample \mathcal{C}
· Output: Action a_t^\pi
· Implementation: PyTorch model (MLP or Transformer) exported to ONNX/TensorRT
· Frequency: Control loop rate (100 Hz)

Module 5: Conformal Safety Monitor

· Input: Predicted state \hat{z}_{t+1}, uncertainty \Sigma_t, quantile \hat{q}_{1-\alpha}
· Output: Boolean safe flag, fallback action if unsafe
· Implementation: Lightweight C++ or Python
· Frequency: Control loop rate (100 Hz)

Module 6: CBF Fallback Controller

· Input: Current state z_t, nominal action a_t^\pi
· Output: Safe action a_t^{\text{safe}}
· Implementation: OSQP solver for CBF-QP
· Frequency: Triggered on demand

6.2.2 Inter-Module Communication

Modules communicate via shared memory when co-located on the same process, or via ROS 2 topics when distributed. The critical real-time path (Perception → Dynamics → Safety → Policy) is optimized for minimal latency:

```
[Camera] → (GStreamer) → [CRL Encoder] → (Shared Memory) → [Dynamics Core]
                                                                    ↓
[Low-Level Controller] ← (EtherCAT/CAN) ← [Safety Monitor] ← [Policy]
```

The causal inference module runs asynchronously and updates the causal mask M_{\mathcal{C}} and neural residual weights in the dynamics core via a thread-safe parameter server.

---

6.3 Real-Time Computational Optimizations

Achieving < 5 ms end-to-end latency on embedded hardware requires careful optimization. We employ the following techniques:

6.3.1 Model Export and Quantization

· CRL Encoder: Exported to TensorRT with FP16 precision. Inference time < 2 ms on Jetson Orin for ResNet-50.
· Policy Network: Exported to ONNX and optimized with TensorRT. Inference time < 0.5 ms for MLP.
· Neural Residual: Small MLP (2 hidden layers, 128 units) with spectral normalization. Inference time < 0.2 ms.

6.3.2 Differentiable Dynamics Optimization

· Mass Matrix Inversion: Cholesky decomposition with Eigen. For n \leq 50, < 0.1 ms.
· LCP Solver: Custom implementation using projected Gauss-Seidel with warm-starting. < 0.5 ms for n_c \leq 10.
· Automatic Differentiation: Disabled at inference time; forward pass uses pre-compiled CUDA kernels from Warp.

6.3.3 Pipeline Parallelism

The perception and control pipelines are decoupled:

· Perception thread: Runs at camera frame rate, updates shared state buffer
· Control thread: Runs at fixed 100 Hz, reads latest state from buffer
· Causal inference thread: Low-priority background thread

This decoupling ensures that control latency is deterministic and unaffected by occasional perception delays.

---

6.4 State and Safety Specifications

6.4.1 State Representation

The latent state z_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d_z} is partitioned as:

z_t = [z_t^{\text{phys}}, z_t^{\delta}]

where:

· z_t^{\text{phys}} \in \mathbb{R}^{n_{\text{phys}}}: Physical state (joint positions, velocities, end-effector pose). For a 7-DOF manipulator, n_{\text{phys}} = 14 (7 positions + 7 velocities).
· z_t^{\delta} \in \mathbb{R}^{n_{\delta}}: Discrepancy state (latent representation of unmodeled mechanisms). Dimension n_{\delta} is a hyperparameter, typically 8-16.

The total latent dimension d_z \approx 30, keeping all matrix operations well within real-time constraints.

6.4.2 Safety Specification

The unsafe set \mathcal{Z}_{\text{unsafe}} is defined by constraints on z^{\text{phys}}:

· Joint limits: q_{\min} \leq q \leq q_{\max}
· Velocity limits: \|\dot{q}\| \leq \dot{q}_{\max}
· End-effector workspace limits
· Obstacle avoidance: distance to known obstacles \geq d_{\text{safe}}

These constraints are encoded as a set of linear inequalities and one nonlinear (obstacle) constraint. The conformal set \hat{C}_t is an ellipsoid in \mathbb{R}^{d_z}. Checking intersection with \mathcal{Z}_{\text{unsafe}} is performed by solving a convex QP: minimize distance from \hat{z}_{t+1} to \mathcal{Z}_{\text{unsafe}} subject to ellipsoid constraint. If the optimal value is \leq 0, intersection occurs.

