Appendix B: Conformal Coverage in Latent Space

This appendix proves Proposition 5.1: coverage guarantee in the learned latent space.

Proof. Let s_t^{\text{true}} = \|s_{t+1}^{\text{real}} - \hat{s}_{t+1}\|_\Sigma be the true nonconformity score in state space. Let z_t = h_\psi(o_t) be the latent representation. The encoder satisfies:

\|z_t - s_t\| \leq \epsilon_h

for some small \epsilon_h > 0 (reconstruction error). The predicted latent state is \hat{z}_{t+1} = f_{\text{sim}+\mathcal{C}}(z_t, a_t). By Lipschitz continuity of the dynamics:

\|\hat{z}_{t+1} - \hat{s}_{t+1}\| \leq L_f \epsilon_h

The nonconformity score in latent space is:

s_t^{\text{latent}} = \|z_{t+1}^{\text{real}} - \hat{z}_{t+1}\|_{\Sigma}

By triangle inequality:

|s_t^{\text{latent}} - s_t^{\text{true}}| \leq \|z_{t+1} - s_{t+1}\| + \|\hat{z}_{t+1} - \hat{s}_{t+1}\| \leq (1 + L_f)\epsilon_h

Let \delta = (1 + L_f)\epsilon_h. The true coverage guarantee states \mathbb{P}(s^{\text{true}} \leq \hat{q}_{1-\alpha}) \geq 1-\alpha. Therefore:

\mathbb{P}(s^{\text{latent}} \leq \hat{q}_{1-\alpha} + \delta) \geq 1-\alpha

By inflating the conformal quantile to \hat{q}_{1-\alpha}' = \hat{q}_{1-\alpha} + \delta, we recover the 1-\alpha guarantee. If \epsilon_h is small (good encoder), the inflation is negligible. ∎

