7.2 Benchmark Selection: REALM and Extensions

7.2.1 REALM Benchmark

We adopt REALM (Real-World Evaluation for Learning-based Manipulation, 2025) as the primary evaluation platform. REALM provides:

· 15 perturbation factors systematically varying visual appearance, physics parameters, and task initialization
· 7 manipulation skills: pick-and-place, stacking, insertion, wiping, pushing, pouring, and tool use
· 3,500+ objects with realistic 3D scans and physical properties
· Pre-evaluated baselines: π₀, π₀-FAST, GR00T N1.5, RT-2-X
· Validated sim-real correlation: The benchmark explicitly quantifies "performance alignment between real-world performance and its simulation counterparts"

REALM's design addresses the "generalization and robustness" challenges that remain open for state-of-the-art vision-language-action models. The benchmark includes both simulated environments (Isaac Sim-based) and a real-world counterpart with identical task specifications, enabling controlled sim-to-real evaluation.

7.2.2 REALM-Causal Extension

We propose extending REALM with causal annotations and contact-rich tasks to evaluate the specific claims of CausalSim++. The extension, which we term REALM-Causal, comprises:

Causal SCM Annotations: For each of 10 selected tasks, we provide ground-truth causal graphs over the state, action, and discrepancy variables. The discrepancy nodes are instantiated as specific physical mechanisms:

Discrepancy Node Physical Interpretation Example Tasks
\delta_{\text{fric}} Friction modeling error (hysteresis, Stribeck) Pushing, sliding
\delta_{\text{comp}} Joint/link compliance Peg insertion, heavy payload
\delta_{\text{contact}} Contact stiffness/damping Grasping, stacking
\delta_{\text{act}} Actuator backlash, torque ripple Precise positioning
\delta_{\text{wear}} Time-varying material properties Repeated insertion

These annotations serve as ground truth for evaluating causal discovery algorithms and for generating synthetic data with controlled structural mismatches.

Contact-Rich Task Suite: We add three tasks specifically designed to stress-test differentiable contact dynamics and causal residual learning:

1. Cable Routing: Threading a flexible cable through a series of clips. Success requires accurate modeling of cable compliance and friction.
2. Cloth Folding: Folding a deformable cloth along a specified line. The task involves complex contact interactions and material hysteresis.
3. Connector Insertion: Inserting a USB-C or circular connector with tight tolerances. Success depends on precise contact modeling and compliance compensation.

These tasks are implemented in both simulation (using NVIDIA Isaac Sim with Flex for deformables) and on real hardware (Franka Emika Panda with external cameras).

Evaluation Harness: We provide a standardized evaluation script that:

· Runs policy rollouts in simulation under varied perturbation factors
· Computes all metrics defined in Section 7.3
· Generates bootstrap confidence intervals
· Produces publication-ready plots and tables

The REALM-Causal extension will be open-sourced upon publication to facilitate reproducible research in causal sim-to-real transfer.

