7.3 Evaluation Metrics

7.3.1 Primary Metrics

Sim-to-Real Transfer Ratio (STR):

\text{STR} = \frac{J_{\text{real}}(\pi)}{J_{\text{sim}}(\pi)}

where J(\pi) is the average episodic return. STR > 0.85 indicates successful zero-shot transfer. We report mean and 95% bootstrap confidence intervals over 30 trials per task.

Success Rate: Binary task completion within a maximum episode length. For insertion, success is defined as full insertion; for pushing, reaching the target zone; for stacking, stable placement without toppling.

Physical Trajectory Divergence: Dynamic Time Warping (DTW) distance between simulated and real trajectories, normalized by trajectory length:

\text{DTW}_{\text{norm}} = \frac{1}{T} \text{DTW}(\tau_{\text{sim}}, \tau_{\text{real}})

Lower values indicate better sim-to-real alignment.

Causal Discovery F1 Score: For tasks with ground-truth SCM annotations, we compute the F1 score of recovered edges:

\text{F1} = \frac{2 \cdot \text{Precision} \cdot \text{Recall}}{\text{Precision} + \text{Recall}}

We report both edge-level (binary presence) and mechanism-level (correct identification of \delta node activation).

7.3.2 Safety and Efficiency Metrics

Safety Violation Rate: Proportion of episodes in which any safety constraint (joint limits, force/torque bounds, collision) is violated. Target: \leq 2\%.

Fallback Activation Rate: Proportion of timesteps where the conformal safety monitor triggers the CBF fallback controller. Lower is better, but must be balanced against safety.

Prediction Set Volume: For conformal methods, the average volume of the prediction ellipsoid \hat{C}_t. Smaller volume indicates higher efficiency.

Sample Efficiency: Number of real-world trajectories required to achieve 80% of asymptotic success rate. Target: \leq 15.

7.3.3 Computational Metrics

Inference Latency: End-to-end latency from observation to action, measured on target hardware (Jetson Orin AGX). Target: \leq 5 ms at 100 Hz control frequency.

Memory Footprint: GPU and CPU memory usage of deployed models.

