8.1 Summary of Contributions

This dissertation has made four primary contributions, each addressing a fundamental gap in the sim-to-real transfer literature.

8.1.1 Causal SCM for Sim-to-Real Gap Characterization

Contribution: We formalized the sim-to-real gap as a partially identifiable Structural Causal Model over physical discrepancy nodes \Delta. This formulation shifts the problem from blind parameter randomization to structured causal discovery, enabling interpretable identification of the specific physical mechanisms missing from simulation.

Key Results:

· Theorem 2.1 established sample complexity bounds for partial identifiability: N = \tilde{O}(|\Delta| \log |\Delta| / \epsilon^2) interventional trajectories suffice to recover the causal graph up to Markov equivalence.
· Theorem 2.2 proved that Bayesian model averaging over the Markov equivalence class yields bounded performance degradation, providing robustness to structural uncertainty.
· Algorithm 2.1 provided a practical causal discovery algorithm combining kernel conditional independence tests with NOTEARS optimization.

Significance: This contribution provides the structural knowledge that distinguishes CausalSim++ from black-box sim-to-real methods. By identifying why the simulator is wrong, we enable targeted compensation and interpretable debugging.

8.1.2 Causal-Structured Hybrid Contact Dynamics

Contribution: We developed a differentiable hybrid dynamics model that augments analytical rigid-body dynamics with neural residuals that are structurally constrained by the discovered causal graph. The formulation preserves physical conservation laws while learning to compensate for unmodeled contact phenomena.

Key Results:

· Equation 3.1 defined the hybrid dynamics: M\ddot{q} + C\dot{q} + g = J_c^\top \lambda + \phi_{\text{neural}}(q, \dot{q}, \lambda; \mathcal{C}) + \tau.
· Theorem 3.2 proved exponential stability of the closed-loop system under PD control, with stability condition L < \lambda_{\min}(K_d)/\|J_c\|^2.
· Proposition 3.1 showed that causal masking reduces the effective Lipschitz constant, relaxing the stability condition and improving out-of-distribution robustness.
· Algorithm 3.1 provided a real-time forward pass with <2 ms latency on edge hardware.

Significance: This contribution provides the functional compensation for the structural gaps identified by the causal SCM. By constraining neural residuals to causally justified edges, we achieve both sample efficiency and formal stability guarantees.

8.1.3 Conformal Causal Safety Filtering

Contribution: We unified causal residual prediction with split-conformal inference to yield finite-sample, distribution-free safety certificates for zero-shot deployment. The safety monitor triggers a provably safe fallback controller when the conformal prediction set intersects the unsafe region.

Key Results:

· Theorem 4.2 proved that the conformal prediction set achieves coverage probability \geq 1-\alpha under trajectory exchangeability.
· Theorem 4.3 established that coverage holds even when the causal graph is imperfectly recovered—a critical robustness property.
· Theorem 4.4 proved that causal correction reduces prediction set volume compared to black-box conformal methods, leading to fewer unnecessary fallback interventions.
· Algorithm 4.3 provided a real-time safety filter operating at control frequency.

Significance: This contribution provides the safety certification that enables confident deployment of learned policies on real hardware. It is the first framework to combine causal structure discovery with conformal prediction for robotics safety.

8.1.4 Perception-to-Causal-State via Causal Representation Learning

Contribution: We bridged the perception gap by integrating causal representation learning to map high-dimensional observations to a disentangled causal latent space. This enables the entire CausalSim++ pipeline to operate directly from pixels without ground-truth state access.

Key Results:

· Algorithm 5.1 provided a three-phase training procedure: simulator pretraining, causal consistency regularization, and real-world finetuning.
· Proposition 5.1 proved that conformal coverage guarantees transfer to latent space with bounded inflation.

Significance: This contribution makes CausalSim++ deployable on real robots with only camera and proprioceptive sensors. It connects the theoretical framework to practical perception systems.

8.1.5 Unified Architecture and Real-Time Deployment

Contribution: We designed CausalSim++ as a modular, real-time pipeline deployable on edge hardware (NVIDIA Jetson Orin). The architecture achieves <5 ms end-to-end latency at 100 Hz for systems up to 50 DOF.

Key Results:

· Chapter 6 detailed the six-module architecture with well-defined interfaces.
· We specified computational optimizations including TensorRT export, custom LCP solver, and pipeline parallelism.

Significance: This contribution demonstrates that the theoretical framework is practically implementable on current robotic hardware, bridging the gap between theory and deployment.

