8.2 Positioning Within the 2025-2026 Landscape

As documented throughout this dissertation, the 2025-2026 period has witnessed an explosion of work at the intersection of causality, world models, and sim-to-real transfer. It is essential to articulate what CausalSim++ contributes that is not already present in this rapidly evolving literature.

8.2.1 Distinction from Foundation World Models

Foundation world models such as NVIDIA Cosmos Policy, LingBot-VA, and Astra demonstrate impressive zero-shot visual prediction capabilities. However, as we have argued (Section 2.1.3, Section 5.1.3), these models:

· Lack formal contact consistency: They generate visually plausible futures but do not enforce conservation of momentum, non-penetration, or friction cone constraints.
· Use "causal" in a different sense: Temporal causal attention masks future frames for autoregressive prediction, but does not discover mechanistic cause-effect relationships.
· Provide no safety certificates: Their predictions come with no formal guarantees on coverage or constraint satisfaction.

CausalSim++ is complementary to these models, not competitive. It provides the physical consistency, causal interpretability, and safety certification that vision-centric predictors currently lack. A promising future direction is to integrate CausalSim++'s causal-physics layer as a consistency module for foundation world models.

8.2.2 Distinction from Residual Dynamics Methods

Residual dynamics methods (Sym2Real, ASAP, ReDRAW) share our goal of learning to compensate for sim-to-real mismatch. However, our causal masking approach (Section 3.2) offers distinct advantages:

· Interpretability: Each non-zero weight corresponds to a specific causal mechanism, enabling debugging and targeted improvement.
· OOD Robustness: Causal constraints prevent the model from learning spurious correlations that fail under distribution shift.
· Formal Stability: The Lipschitz bound and stability proof (Theorem 3.2) rely on the sparsity induced by causal masking.

8.2.3 Distinction from Conformal Safety Methods

Conformal prediction for robotics safety has been explored in several recent works (Staggered Integral OCP, Conformal Reachability). Our contribution is the causal conditioning of the nonconformity score. By computing residuals on causally corrected predictions, we obtain:

· Tighter prediction sets (Theorem 4.4), reducing unnecessary fallback interventions.
· Attributable uncertainty: The residual magnitude can be decomposed into contributions from specific discrepancy nodes, guiding future model improvements.

8.2.4 Distinction from Prior Causal Sim-to-Real Work

Maldonado et al. (ERF 2025) and C²-Net (2025) have validated the use of causal discovery for sim-to-real gap analysis. Our framework extends this line of work by:

· Online compensation: We use the discovered SCM for real-time control, not just post-hoc analysis.
· Differentiable contact: We integrate causal structure with LCP-based contact dynamics, essential for manipulation.
· Safety certification: We provide formal guarantees that prior causal sim-to-real work does not.

---

8.3 Limitations of the Proposed Framework

Despite its contributions, CausalSim++ has several limitations that must be acknowledged.

8.3.1 Dependence on a Differentiable Simulator

CausalSim++ requires a differentiable simulator to enable gradient-based training of the neural residual and to compute the LCP solution. While differentiable simulators are increasingly available (Warp, MJX, Brax), they may not exist for all robotic platforms or may not accurately model all relevant physics. The framework is less applicable to systems where a high-fidelity differentiable simulator is unavailable.

8.3.2 Candidate Discrepancy Set Specification

The causal discovery algorithm (Algorithm 2.1) requires a pre-specified candidate set \Delta of discrepancy mechanisms. If the true structural mismatch involves a mechanism not in \Delta, it will be absorbed into the neural residual without causal interpretation. While Theorem 2.4 ensures graceful degradation, the full benefits of interpretability and tight safety bounds are only realized when \Delta covers the true mismatches.

8.3.3 Exchangeability Assumption for Conformal Coverage

The split-conformal coverage guarantee (Theorem 4.2) relies on the exchangeability of calibration and test trajectories. This assumption may be violated if:

· The environment changes between calibration and deployment (e.g., lighting, surface properties)
· The robot undergoes wear or thermal drift over time
· The deployment policy differs significantly from the safe exploration policy used for calibration

Section 4.6 discussed online conformal prediction as a mitigation, but this requires additional validation.

8.3.4 Computational Overhead of Causal Discovery

While the forward pass of CausalSim++ is real-time capable, the offline causal discovery phase (NOTEARS optimization) scales as O(|\mathbf{V}|^3). For high-dimensional state spaces (e.g., humanoids with n>50), this may become prohibitive. Sparse structure learning techniques and GPU-accelerated solvers can mitigate this, but remain a limitation for very large systems.

8.3.5 CRL Encoder Sensitivity

The CRL encoder's performance depends on the quality of simulation pretraining and the domain gap between simulated and real visuals. While we employ domain randomization and cycle consistency, there is no theoretical guarantee that the encoder will perfectly recover causal variables from real images. The conformal safety filter provides robustness, but extreme visual domain shifts could still cause failures.

8.3.6 No Physical Validation

As explicitly scoped, this dissertation presents a theoretical and architectural framework without physical experiments. The claims and predictions in Chapter 7 await empirical validation. This is a significant limitation; the true test of any sim-to-real method is on hardware.

---

8.4 Future Research Directions

The limitations discussed above suggest several promising directions for future work.

8.4.1 Online Causal Structure Learning

Currently, the causal graph is discovered offline from calibration data and remains fixed during deployment. However, the sim-to-real gap may evolve over time due to wear, maintenance, or environmental changes. Online causal discovery would update the graph as new data arrives, maintaining accurate causal structure throughout the robot's lifetime.

Technical challenges include:

· Streaming causal discovery algorithms with bounded memory
· Detecting structural changes (concept drift in causal mechanisms)
· Safe exploration during online learning

8.4.2 Integration with Tactile Sensing for Faster Identifiability

Tactile sensors (e.g., GelSight, uSkin) provide direct observations of contact forces, friction, and local geometry. Integrating tactile feedback could dramatically accelerate causal discovery of contact-related discrepancy nodes. For instance, a single grasp with a tactile sensor might reveal the true friction coefficient and contact stiffness, bypassing the need for multiple interventional trajectories.

8.4.3 Extension to Multi-Agent and Human-Robot Interaction

CausalSim++ currently models a single robot interacting with a passive environment. Extending to multi-agent systems and human-robot interaction introduces exogenous agents whose behavior cannot be intervened upon. This requires causal discovery under latent confounding, a significantly harder problem. Recent work on causal discovery with unobserved confounders (e.g., FCI algorithm) provides a starting point.

8.4.4 Combining with Foundation Models for Visual Prediction

A promising synthesis is to use foundation world models (e.g., Cosmos, LingBot-VA) for visual prediction while using CausalSim++ as a physics-consistency filter. The foundation model generates candidate futures; CausalSim++ checks them against causal-physics constraints and rejects those that violate conservation laws or contact consistency. This hybrid approach could combine the visual fidelity of foundation models with the formal guarantees of our framework.

8.4.5 Learning the Discrepancy Node Functional Forms

Currently, the functional forms \phi_i for discrepancy nodes are learned as neural networks. An alternative is to learn symbolic expressions for these mechanisms (e.g., via genetic programming or equation discovery). Symbolic forms would be even more interpretable and could be directly incorporated into analytical simulators, closing the loop on simulator improvement.

8.4.6 Formal Verification of Neural Residuals

While Theorem 3.2 provides stability under a Lipschitz bound, verifying that a trained neural network actually satisfies this bound is non-trivial. Future work could employ formal verification tools (e.g., SMT solvers, interval bound propagation) to certify the Lipschitz constant of \phi_{\text{neural}} at deployment time, providing stronger guarantees.

8.4.7 Hardware-in-the-Loop Validation

The most urgent next step is to implement CausalSim++ on physical hardware and validate the theoretical predictions from Chapter 7. This requires:

· Building the REALM-Causal evaluation harness
· Collecting calibration trajectories on a Franka Panda or similar platform
· Implementing the full software stack on Jetson Orin
· Conducting systematic comparisons against baselines

This empirical validation is the natural continuation of this dissertation.

