8.5 Broader Impact

8.5.1 Towards Safe and Reliable Robot Learning

The central promise of sim-to-real transfer is to enable robots to learn complex skills in simulation and deploy them directly in the real world, bypassing the cost and risk of real-world trial-and-error. However, the brittleness of current sim-to-real methods—their tendency to fail silently when encountering unmodeled physics—has limited adoption in safety-critical domains.

CausalSim++ addresses this brittleness by providing formal safety certificates and interpretable failure modes. If a deployment fails, the causal graph identifies which physical mechanism caused the mismatch, enabling targeted simulator improvement. If the conformal monitor triggers, it does so with a statistical guarantee on coverage, allowing operators to trust the fallback behavior.

This work is a step toward a future where learned policies are deployed with the same level of confidence as traditional model-based controllers, unlocking applications in:

· Industrial automation: Rapid reconfiguration of assembly lines without extensive real-world tuning
· Healthcare robotics: Safe deployment of assistive robots in homes and hospitals
· Space robotics: Training in simulation then deploying on planetary rovers where real-world testing is impossible
· Disaster response: Quickly adapting learned skills to novel, hazardous environments

8.5.2 Open Science and Reproducibility

We are committed to open-sourcing the CausalSim++ codebase and the REALM-Causal extension upon publication. This will enable the research community to:

· Reproduce our theoretical results
· Benchmark new causal discovery and sim-to-real methods
· Extend the framework to new robots and tasks

Open science is particularly important in sim-to-real research, where proprietary simulators and closed datasets have historically hindered reproducibility.

8.5.3 Ethical Considerations

Any technology that enables autonomous robots to operate with less human supervision raises ethical questions. The safety certification in CausalSim++ is a technical guarantee, not a substitute for responsible deployment practices. We emphasize:

· Human oversight: The conformal safety monitor provides probabilistic, not absolute, guarantees. Human supervision remains essential, especially in early deployments.
· Transparency: The causal graph provides interpretability, which can aid in auditing and accountability.
· Dual use: Like all robotics research, this work could be misused. We advocate for responsible development and adherence to ethical guidelines.

8.5.4 Standards and Regulation

As autonomous robots become more prevalent, standards bodies (e.g., ISO/TC 299 for robotics, ISO 3691-5 for industrial trucks) are developing safety requirements for learned components. The formal guarantees provided by CausalSim++—finite-sample coverage, exponential stability under Lipschitz residuals—align with the emerging emphasis on certifiable AI. Engaging with these standards early could help shape regulations that are both safe and innovation-friendly.

