8.6 Concluding Remarks

This dissertation has presented CausalSim++, a unified framework for zero-shot sim-to-real transfer grounded in causal discovery, differentiable contact dynamics, and conformal safety certification. We have shown that by formalizing the sim-to-real gap as a partially identifiable Structural Causal Model, we can replace blind parameter randomization with structured, sample-efficient discovery. By constraining neural residuals to the discovered causal graph, we achieve both physical consistency and formal stability guarantees. And by wrapping the entire pipeline in a conformal safety filter, we provide finite-sample, distribution-free deployment certificates.

The framework does not claim to solve all sim-to-real challenges. It requires a differentiable simulator, a candidate set of discrepancy mechanisms, and calibration trajectories collected under safe exploration. It does not eliminate the need for real-world testing. But it does provide a principled, theoretically grounded approach to an important class of problems: contact-rich manipulation tasks where structural mismatches dominate the sim-to-real gap.

In an era of rapidly advancing foundation models for robotics, it is tempting to believe that scale alone will solve sim-to-real transfer. This dissertation argues otherwise: physical consistency, causal structure, and formal safety guarantees are not optional luxuries—they are essential prerequisites for deploying learned policies in the real world. CausalSim++ demonstrates that these desiderata can be achieved without sacrificing real-time performance or sample efficiency, offering a path toward robots that learn in simulation and act with confidence in reality.

